        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              If you're interested in the all-rounder/flanking style of mediums, the American line is also very nice. It has several stand-out tanks, the two most highlighted are probably the T6 M4E8 (or Easy Eight) and the T8 M26 Pershing. Both are very balanced and serious fun. I wound up going down the German medium tree to T8 - and although I've heard the E50 is great fun fully kitted out, for me the tree stops at T6 with the awesome VKs - 3601 and 3001H are both great, in different ways.<br /><br />On the TD side, Germans get to the land of heavy frontal armor the quickest, and pretty much stay that way. Americans have the option of turreted TDs, which is an interested play style which people often make the mistake of playing like tanks. Russians start off with fairly low armor, but get big guns pretty quickly, and the last few are an interesting combo of good armor (frontal), huge gun and reasonable speed.<br /><br />The Heavy lines can (generally) be boiled down to this: German - sloped armor that requires angling, accurate guns. American - very strong turrets, balanced accuracy/damage/reload. Russian - slower, lower, generally highest &quot;alpha&quot; for their tier (per shot damage), heavy armor.<br /><br />Americans get lots of love when you can cover your hull, since their very high turret armor combines nicely with their higher then average depression, allowing shots when all the opponant can shoot back at is something they cant penetrate. Germans are generally best at range, where they can angle their armor (rotating the tank at a slight offset to incoming rounds to increase the effective armor) and take advantage of their accurage. Russians like to get up close and brawl, the later tanks do get some accurate guns though.<br /><br />Edit: I tried to play a couple games over the weekend, hopped in to the ELC just to see what's up, and it's highly amusing. I can totally see why you guys are calling it the new troll tank. Only downside is the reload (well, and the one shottable nature of it, got derped by a 122), but it's pretty accurate. Ran one game in my T20, wound up playing peekaboo with some much larger tanks, walked out with a 600ish xp loss. Fun times, looking forward to getting back in the game here in two weeks.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
