        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Tier 4 is going to suck, no matter what you do. You just have to get through it. It represents the late interwar period when all the great powers were churning out new-fangled but wrongheaded infantry tanks and mini-land-dreadnoughts. They show their suckage when up against tier 5 and higher, which represent tank design that begins to respond to WWII-experience-hardened armour doctrine. Suffice it to say they all kinda suck. The Soviet T-28 might be the only exception to those, owing to its fantastic gunnage and relatively peppy mobility (and not being a light tank, so it gets proper tiering). The M5 Stuart and PzIII are also decent, but lights, so you get that tiering problem.<br /><br />But the overall point here is grit your teeth and push through whatever tier 4 tank you have, and then prepare to bask in the glory that is tier 5, as far as I'm concerned one of the best overall tiers in the game, with a vast multitude of tanks in every nation that are well-rounded, capable, profit-making and fun. M4 Sherman, PzIV, T-34, KV-1 (if you like slow heavies), ELC AMX, T49, M10 Wolverine, the list goes on. All good to great tanks that you will either keep when you move beyond them, or buy back later on and absolutely stuff with equipment and play for shits and giggles.<br /><br />Tier 5 is great. And it's all good from there on. Grinding doesn't get too seriously long until tier 7ish, and noticeably at tier 8.<br /><br />Side note: SPGs accumulate XP at a slower pace, and have higher XP requirements to transition up the tier levels, so if you play them, be prepared to spend a lot longer in each tier than you would in a tank.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
