          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Are these posts still valid for explaining different types of tanks and Nations?<br /><!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=22976025#p22976025">viewtopic.php?p=22976025#p22976025</a><!-- l --><br /><!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=22976230#p22976230">viewtopic.php?p=22976230#p22976230</a><!-- l --><br /><br />Also, I didn't worry much about equipment or consumables or buying training for my crew until I hit Tier 5 mediums and I started &quot;swimming&quot; in credits.<br /><br />As I mentioned last page the best RoI for your tank is getting the modules, like top turret, top gun etc.  The next best is getting your crew up to 100%, which is hard at lower tiers.  Then there's the equipment and consumables.<br /><br />I really didn't like using consumables until I got the Tier 5 medium tanks and then I would earn enough credits in a battle to buy 1 to 3 consumables and in 4 or 5 battles to buy training for the crew.<br /><br />The first equipment purchase was a camo net at 50,000 credits (which was half off).  Camo nets, Binoculars, and toolbox can be removed at will at no gold cost.  Everything else either costs gold or gets destroyed.<br /><br />I do recommend getting into channel with one of the more experienced folk.  Some of us maintain really low tier tanks because it's different than playing at high tier.<br /><br />Final note: When you're moving, plan to move from cover to cover or concealment.  If you're fired upon, take some pot shots, but goal 1 is to get to cover.  The new players tend to sit out in that open field to return fire and get slaughtered because they're sitting duck and not trying to move to cover.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
